          <section xml:id="sec-webster-huntington">
            <title>The Webster and Huntington-Hill Methods of Apportionment</title>
            <introduction>
              <p>
                We may proceed through the remaining methods of apportionment
                more quickly. The fundamental concepts in place above are 
                only slightly altered in the following approaches. With both
                Hamilton and Jefferson methods, the driving idea was finding 
                the divisor, then finding a way to apportion the remaining
                representatives after whole numbers have been given. For the
                remaining two methods, the Webster Method and the Huntington-Hill
                Method, the second of which is still (as of 2025) being used 
                by the USA, the approach involves adjustment of the divisor,
                similar to the Jefferson Method, combined with a system of 
                rounding to whole numbers. In both Hamilton and Jefferson 
                methods, recall that we round down (or <term>truncate</term>)
                the result of dividing the population by the divisor. For
                the Webster Method, we simply round to the nearest whole 
                number in the usual way: by rounding down if the fractional
                portion is less than 0.5 and rounding up if the fractional
                portion is larger than 0.5. (In the unlikely event that the
                fractional portion is exactly 0.5, the usual rule is to round
                up.) For Huntington-Hill Method, the boundary for rounding
                up is made more generous. We will explore this in detail
                in examples.
              </p>
            </introduction>
