      <chapter xml:id="ch-weighted-voting">
        <title>Power in Weighted Voting Systems</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            All of the effort put into the systems described in the previous chapter were premised upon an
            intuitive idea: that if a state has, for example, twice the representatives, then it will have
            twice the power in the House of Representatives. But remember: one of the overarching themes of
            this book is that we want to be able to use mathematics and its related fields to investigate 
            whether our intuitive ideas about how things work are, in fact, accurate. We have already seen
            some examples of how this can happen. But the belief related to this idea of power is quite
            surprising and can be motivated with a relatively simple example.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-weighted-intuition">
            <title>Intuition Misleading Us?</title>
            <p>
              Suppose there were three states in the nation with populations such that, 
              in the 100-member House
              of Representatives, one state, Alsaka, had 49 representatives, 
              one state, Bartleby, had 47 representatives, and a third
              state, Cropland, had four representatives. 
              Let us further assume that these numbers of representatives are
              proportional to population. 
              (For example, this would be exactly true if the populations were 49,000, 
              47,000, and 4000, respectively.) 
              So according to the intuition we have
              been basing our work on up until now, this system has been constructed 
              in a way that is fair. It has explicitly and exactly matched the proportion of 
              numbers of representatives to the proportion of the number of people in the
              population for each state. The state that has 49% of the population has
              49% of the representatives, the state that has 47% of the population has 47% of
              the representatives, and the state that has 4% of the population has 4% of 
              the representatives.
              (If you look back at examples and exercises from 
              <xref ref="ch-democracy-representation"/> you will notice that in practice
              it will almost never happen that these proportions match so exactly. We have, 
              in a sense, imagined what seems to be a rather ideal situation for fairness
              in the proportional representation of these states in this legislative body.)
              Our intuition has told us and our justification for all
              the work in <xref ref="ch-democracy-representation"/> is based on the idea that
              this should preserve those proportions, as well, in terms of decision-making
              power. That is, if you have 49% of the representatives, you should have
              roughly 49% of the decision-making power, similarly 47% of the representatives
              should give you 47% of the decision-making power, and 4% of the representatives
              should give you 4% of the decision-making power.
            </p>
            <p>
              Before we proceed further, if you were to guess how powerful each state was
              in the legislature, what would you say? Does it match the percentages
              described above? Or is the state with 49,000 people twice
              as powerful as the state with 4000 people? Five times as powerful? (Note: you
              should not feel bad if you have only a vague sense of this. <q>Power</q> is
              a concept that we have not carefully defined. Indeed, that is the point of this
              section, to develop a coherent approach to thinking mathematically about 
              how power might be quantified in such situations.)
            </p>
            <p>
              So let us suppose that these states have quite distinct populations and, further,
              let us suppose that each state delegation is disciplined and loyal and always
              votes together as a group. (If you think this changes your idea of the power of
              each state, that seems reasonable to me. Interesting how quickly assumptions
              and constraints change our ideas about how a system works, no?)
            </p>
            <p>
              How do things play out? Well let us think it through: Suppose the proposed
              measure that this legislative body is deliberating upon is whether to 
              locate a (necessary?) toxic
              waste dump in Cropland. We might expect this to be approved by the 49
              representatives from Alsaka and the 47 from Bartleby, which would allow
              the measure to pass by majority vote. (Note that there is another assumption
              here, one we might do well to (re)consider later, namely that simple majority,
              which in this case would be 51 out of 100, is all that is needed to
              pass a measure.) Obviously 96 votes will suffice to pass the measure.
              That is to say: if both Alsaka and Bartleby favor a measure, then that 
              measure will be approved by the legislative body. 
            </p>
            <p>
              But suppose, instead, that a measure were introduced to place the 
              waste dump in Alsaka? Why, then we might expect that Bartleby and
              Cropland could agree to vote in favor of this measure, which would
              thus pass by a 51 to 49 count. A measure passed by 51 to 49 is just as
              binding as a measure passed by 96 to 4. This fact turns out to have
              a rather interesting consequence. In fact, we can now notice the 
              following key fact: 
              <em>
                If two of the three states are in favor of a measure, then
                the measure will pass.
              </em>
              This may be quite surprising, even disturbing. Especially since
              it shows that our intuition about the scaling of representatives
              to population might completely fail to scale the decision-making
              power in the way we had hoped. Alsaka has the same amount of 
              power in this system as Cropland does, despite the fact that its
              population is over 12 times bigger. A citizen of Alsaka has 
              less than 
              <m>
                \frac{1}{12}
              </m>
              the amount of power as a citizen of Cropland. It is not unreasonable
              to think that over time this sort of distortion away from 
              <q>equal representation</q> might have rather significant effects
              upon the views citizens might have of the legitimacy of the 
              political system.
            </p>
            <p>
              Note that we have different ways we might think of the power
              in this system and how it is distributed. Based on previous
              ways we have been thinking about such things, we might
              choose to think of there being 100% of power that must be 
              distributed. Then in this case we would say that each 
              state has roughly 33% of the power. We could similarly 
              declare that all the power adds to 1 and say that each
              state has power measured at 0.33. 
              <aside>
                There is nothing preventing us from declaring there to be
                any amount of power which must be distributed. We might 
                set up our analysis such that 45 <q>power units</q> are 
                available to be distributed in the system. Then our analysis
                would conclude in this case that each state has 15 power
                units. But can you see how this is really just introducing a
                rather arbitrary additional number into the process? Is this
                not rather slightly illuminating to say that Cropland has 15
                of the 45 power units? It is easier just to say it has 33.3%
                of the power or 0.333 of the power.
              </aside>
            </p>
          </example>
          <p>
            Before we move on to a more systematic approach to computing power
            within a system like this, let us first notice how sensitive such 
            a system might be to changes in the conditions of the population.
          </p>
          <example>
            <p>
              Suppose a decade passes, and during that time
              1500 people move from State Bartleby to Alsaka and 
              500 from Cropland to Alsaka (but all other births and deaths
              cancel out so the only changes are these relocations). Now what?
            </p>
          </example>
          <p>
            In a rather beautiful demonstration of the fact that math and
            quantitative reasoning are creative processes, there are two 
            main approaches to computing the power available to each state
            in a system like this. The numbers they produce are sometimes the
            same but often are not. Each conceives of what matters in a different
            way, which we will summarize as the power in saying no and the 
            power in saying yes.
          </p>
          <p>
            One final task before we begin: the terminology and assumptions
            we will use throughout the following analysis. To achieve a sort 
            of generality of application, we will abstract slightly from the 
            descriptions above. Rather than states we will think of 
            <term>players</term> in a <term>weighted voting system</term>. 
            Each player will have a <term>weight</term>, and the system
            itself will have a <term>quota</term>, which is the required
            total weight of players required to pass a measure.
          </p>
          <p>
            To make this clear, in <xref ref="ex-weighted-intuition"/>, 
            there are
            three players, Alsaka with weight 49, Bartleby with weight 47, 
            and Cropland with weight 4. The quota in that example is 51. We 
            always require that the quota exceed half the total weight of the 
            system. (Why must we insist on this? How would the system potentially
            break down if we failed to require this?) Our notation for such a
            system will be: 
            <me>
              [51:49,47,4]  
            </me>
            We will always write the weights in descending order after the colon.
            More generally if we have <m>n</m> players, <m>P_1, P_2, \dots, P_n</m>
            with weights (in descending order)  <m>w_1, w_2, \dots, w_n</m> and 
            quota <m>q</m>, we will denote this weighted voting system as:
            <me>
              [q:w_1,w_2,\dots,w_n]
            </me>
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <section xml:id="sec-no-power">
          <title>The Power of No</title>
          <p>
            Our purpose in this section is to explore how we might measure
            power in a weighted voting system by the ability to say 
            <q>No!</q> to a measure and for that <q>No!</q> to matter. An 
            easy first step is to say that if it were impossible that a 
            <q>No!</q> from some player could matter, then this player
            has no power in the system. We might also say that player has
            zero power. We call such a player a <term>dummy</term>.          
          </p>
          <p>
            At the other end of this spectrum, if there is some player
            with so much weight that if they say <q>No!</q> to a measure
            then that measure can never pass, we say this player has
            <term>veto power</term> in the system. You may think that
            such a player must have all the power in the system, but 
            this is actually not the case.
            <example xml:id="ex-veto">
              <p>
                Consider the weighted voting system <m>[4:3,2,1]</m>.
                Since Player 2 and Player 3 only add to a total weight of 3, 
                this means they cannot pass a measure without Player 1. 
                Thus, Player 1 has veto power. But notice that Player 1 cannot
                pass a measure on their own, because their weight is also
                3, which is less than the quota, <m>q=4</m>. Neither Player 2
                nor Player 3 have veto power. But it also seems they may not
                be a dummies. (We will develop our abilities further to explore
                this question.)
              </p>
            </example>
            It turns out that it is possible that more than one player 
            might have veto power within a system:
            <example xml:id="ex-veto-multiple">
              <p>
                Consider the weighted voting system <m>[6:4,3,1]</m>. If
                we think about what is required to pass a measure in this 
                system, we see that Player 1 is needed, but so is Player 2.
                Player 1 and Player 3, even if they agree, do not reach
                the total weight required by the quota <m>q=6</m>. Similarly,
                Player 2 and Player 3, even if they agree, do not reach
                the quota. Thus,
                both Player 1 and Player 2 have veto power in this system.
                If either Player 1 or Player 2 say no to a measure, it will
                not pass.
                (It may be the case, now, that Player 3 is indeed a dummy.
                But we need, still, to develop our tools to be able to 
                explore this.)
              </p>
            </example>
          </p>
          <p>
            In order to systematically explore the Power of No (often called 
            <q>the Banzhaf power index</q>) we need to introduce the idea
            of a <term>winning coalition</term>. A winning coalition is any
            set of players which can pass a measure; that is, a winning 
            coalition is any set of players whose total weight meets or exceeds
            the quota.
          </p>
          <p>
            The first step in computing the Power of No in a weighted
            voting system is to write down all
            the winning coalitions for that system.
          </p>
        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-yes-power">
          <title>The Power of Yes</title>
          <p>
            POWER OF YES
          </p>
        </section>
      </chapter>

      <chapter xml:id="ch-financial-math">
        <title>Financial Mathematics</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            You are enmeshed in a system that insists upon your compliance
            in order for you to continue to eat. Only willing subjects to
            this system are afforded the calories and nutrients that
            allow their physical and biological substrate to continue to 
            function. If this sounds coercive, you are correct. It is.
          </p>
          <p>
            One of the key implements of coercion and power in the 
            current world system is the monetary system and its associated
            practices of credit and debt. This financial system is 
            massively complex at this point, including huge portions that
            not only run on computers but are controlled by computers, 
            sometimes in ways few humans do <em>or even can</em> 
            understand. The basics of interest, debt, credit, and the time 
            value of money will be covered in this chapter, with the 
            intention that the careful learners emerge better able to 
            protect themselves from those with massive power within
            the system. That is, the very rich.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will begin by introducing the concept of 
            <term>interest</term>, which is nothing more complex
            than a periodic proportional increase in an amount
            of money. Yet in practice what it becomes is a
            fee charged by those with more than enough
            money to live to those with less than enough money
            to live... to live.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will discuss this further once we have established
            the mechanics of the system. But keep this in mind as well:
            as we explore the logic and movement in this system, 
            remember always that it is a human system, contingent,
            changeable. Humanity has arranged its behavior and care
            for each other radically differently for the vast majority
            of human history. 
            <em>
              Economics and finance are often taught and thought as
              if the patterns and practices are as natural and eternal
              as the laws of nature. They are not, and should not be
              thought of that way.
            </em>
            <remark>
              <p>
                The world has been and will be other than it now is.
                View with suspicion those who, comfortable atop a
                heap of the miserable, insist the world can never
                be otherwise.
              </p>
            </remark>
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <section xml:id="sec-interest">
          <title>Interest and Time</title>
          <p>
            We will take the idea of money as given, though, again, 
            one must keep in mind that it is only a contingent set
            of human practices that allow it to so thoroughly organize
            our lives.
          </p>
          <p>
            Once money is posited as part of the system, as a sort of 
            universal unit of exchange that can provide access to
            goods and services, necessary and frivolous alike, the issue
            of time also presents itself. Specifically, how does (or 
            should?) time and money interact. One way is that you do 
            or will eventually trade away part of your life to your
            boss, a portion of each of your finite number of days, in 
            exchange for money. This money can, in theory, then be 
            used to provide food and shelter and medical care to you
            and those you love.
          </p>
          <p>
            Throughout this book, we have often found ourselves in 
            pursuit of equivalents. (Or <q>equivalence</q>.) Here we find
            another needed pursuit: suppose you need money right now and 
            someone else has that money. Further, that person does not 
            need the money they have for use right now. They could give
            the money to you for you to use for the needed food or housing
            or medical care. They might ask only for the same amount of money
            in return at some future (specified or unspecified) date. 
            This rarely occurs. Generally, a larger amount of future money is
            expected in return.
          </p>
          <p>
            There are a variety of reasons that might be given for this
            expectation. We might even view some of them as, more or 
            less, reasonable. What we must never do is lose sight of the
            fact that any such reason runs the risk of becoming so encrusted,
            even completely obscured by habit and privilege, that it
            becomes an item of faith upon which the lives and well-being of
            vulnerable people will be sacrificed without hesitation. 
          </p>
          <p>
            So let us present the reasons that the future repayment might
            be expected to be larger than the original loan amount, wary and
            with full awareness of the ways
            these reasons can be used to justify privation, want, 
            and exploitation of vulnerable persons. 
          </p>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Risk: the borrower may not pay the agreed future
                  amount, either because they will not or cannot. Thus, 
                  the creditor should be compensated for taking this risk
                  and the amount repaid should be larger than that loaned.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Lost access to the loaned money: the creditor no 
                  longer has the use of the loaned money in the interval
                  between loaning it and being repaid. Thus, the creditor 
                  should be compensated for this decrease in their 
                  financial autonomy 
                  and the amount repaid should be larger than that loaned.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Inflation: historically, on average, the value of 
                  money has a tendency to decrease. This means a dollar now
                  tends to be able to purchase more than a dollar in a
                  month or a year or a decade. (when I was a teen, it cost
                  $7 to see an evening movie. Nowadays, a teen would watch
                  it free via torrent on their phone. But if they went to the
                  theater to see an evening movie it would cost around $15.) 
                  Since a dollar now will (usually) buy less than a dollar in 
                  the future, the creditor should be compensated to mitigate 
                  this decay in purchasing power
                  and the amount repaid should be larger than that loaned.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          <p>
            <example xml:id="ex-time-interest">
              <title>Interest: Borrowing and Repaying</title>              
              <p>
                Mary needs $100 to buy food for her four children. 
                Richard has $100 he is not using and will not need for a 
                month. He agrees to loan Mary money to feed her 
                children as long as she will pay him back an extra 
                10% at the end of the month. Mary has little choice 
                but to agree.
              </p>
              <p>
                How much does Mary pay at the end of the month? We
                know from what we learned in 
                <xref ref="ch-percent-proportion"/>
                that 10% of $100 is: 
                <me>
                  (0.10)(100)=10
                </me>
                So Mary will repay the original $100 plus the 
                extra $10 for a total of $110. We call the
                $10 the <term>interest</term>. We call the 10% 
                the <term>interest rate</term> for the period of
                one month.
              </p>
            </example>
          </p>
        </section>
      </chapter>

      <chapter xml:id="ch-probability">
        <title>How Likely is Some Occurrence?</title>
        <p>
          Now that we are becoming more comfortable with percentages and proportions, why not think about a
          proportion of the time that something happens? It isn't that different, conceptually, to say that 65%
          of some group of 100 people have brown eyes as it is to say that 65% of the 100 days from February 14
          to May 25 have some rain that falls on Seattle at some point during that day.
        </p> 
      </chapter>


      <chapter xml:id="ch-marx-models">
        <title>Marx and his Mathematical Models</title>
        <p>
          The brilliant philosophical and economic thinker, Karl Marx, is one of the most influential 
          minds over the last two centuries, especially in our understanding of the current dominant world
          economic system, capitalism. While it is beyond the scope of this textbook to debate whether Marx
          was right or not (in itself a strange debate, generally driven by ideology rather than honest desire
          for truth) instead we will focus on Marx's clever deployment of mathematical models to help drive
          insight for himself and understanding for others. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Marx was faced with a problem: he saw the dynamic creative potential 
          within capitalism, yet he also clearly saw
          (in a way that far too many self-interested capital boosters now do not) 
          the enormous violence 
          this economic system visited upon those who performed the vast 
          majority of the hazardous and back-breaking
          labor within it. In the face of many theorists before and since, 
          Marx sought a mode of analysis that would
          not only explain the movement of capital and the deployment 
          of labor power, but also might generate
          insights about instability within the system and long-term tendencies. 
          All of this, he is carrying out very 
          near the birth of capitalism and in the context of its early 
          working out of its principles and practices.
        </p>
      </chapter>

      <chapter xml:id="ch-statistics">
        <title>Statistics: Summarizing and Hypothesizing</title>
        
        <section> 
          <title>A Dizzyingly Complex World</title>
          <p>
            A beautiful reality is that we inhabit a universe that is boundlessly complex,
            filled with processes and orders that we have only barely begun to understand. 
            One cannot get very far into the scientific world without hearing a lot about
            statistics, and so we will begin to explore them here.   
          </p>
          <p>
            The key idea for statistics is this: given that our ways of measuring reality
            are many, and given that many groups of objects or phenomena that we might 
            wish to measure and understand are quite numerous, how can we grasp patterns
            or tendencies within these groups? As humans, we have a very limited ability
            to recognize patterns or tendencies from within a huge list of numbers. We 
            simply did not evolve to have intuition for that sort of thing. The field we 
            call <q>statistics</q> is designed precisely to give us methods of summarizing
            and understanding tendencies within groups of objects.
            
            <example>
              <p> 
                Suppose we wished to understand a certain variety of penguin inhabiting
                southerly islands at some point in time. We might wish to undestand the size
                of the adult penguins. Now, size might be measured in a variety of ways: length,
                mass, circumference of head, circumference of torso. 
              </p>
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </example>
          </p>
        </section>
